text: Sanday is one of the inhabited islands of Orkney that lies off the north coast of mainland Scotland. With an area of 50.43 km2 , Sanday is the third largest of the inhabited islands of Orkney. The main centres of population are Lady Village and Kettletoft. Sanday can be reached by Orkney Ferries or by plane from Kirkwall on mainland Scotland. On Sanday, an on demand public minibus service allows connecting to the ferry.

Catterick Camp railway station was a railway station in what is now the Richmondshire district of North Yorkshire, England. Catterick Camp railway station was built as the terminus of the sub branch of the Eryholme Richmond branch line to serve Catterick Camp, now Catterick Garrison. Along with the rest of the stations on the sub branch of the Eryholme Richmond branch line Catterick Camp railway station was closed in 1964. On 15 September 1917, a set of carriages ran away from Catterick Camp railway station and were derailed. Three people were killed.

South Lanarkshire is one of 32 unitary authorities of Scotland. South Lanarkshire borders the south east of the City of Glasgow and contains some of Greater Glasgows suburbs,also containing many towns and villages. South Lanarkshire also shares borders with Dumfries and Galloway, East Ayrshire, East Renfrewshire, North Lanarkshire, the Scottish Borders and West Lothian. South Lanarkshire includes part of the historic county of Lanarkshire.

Hinksey Hill is a hill and residential area 2 miles south of the village. Hinksey Hill was part of Berkshire until the 1974 boundary changes transferred Hinksey Hill to Oxfordshire. At the foot of Hinksey Hill is Hinksey Hill Interchange where the Abingdon By Pass joins the Southern By Pass Road. The road up Hinksey Hill was the route of the A34 until the 1970s, when the Abingdon Bypass was completed. The road up the hill is now an unclassified road. Hinksey Hill has a good view of Oxfords skyline.

Westbury is a village and parish in Shropshire, England. Westbury includes the settlements of Caus Forest, Lake, Marche, Newtown, Stoney Stretton, Vennington, Wallop, Westbury, Whitton, Winsley and Yockleton. It lies 8 miles closed in 2017, merging in a federation with Worthen and Hope into the Long Mountain School at Worthen.

Threshers Bush or Threshers Bush is a hamlet and road in the civil parishes of both Matching and High Laver, and the Epping Forest district of Essex, England. The M11 motorway is 1 mile . Threshers Bush or Threshers Bush public house is The John Barleycorn at the east of Threshers Bush or Threshers Bush

Beckfoot is a hamlet in the civil parish of Holme St Cuthbert in Cumbria, England. Beckfoot is located on the B5300 coast road, three miles south of Silloth on Solway and two miles north of the village of Mawbray. The county town of Carlisle is twenty five miles away to the east.

Sandy railway station serves Sandy. Sandy railway station is on the East Coast Main Line, about 44 miles from London Kings Cross. Sandy is managed and served by Great Northern. Sandy railway station was originally built in 1850 for Great Northern; the London and North Western Railway opened an adjacent station in 1862. The stations were later merged into one, which has since undergone many changes. Sandy railway station has two large platforms and 4 main rail lines, a pair of up and down slow lines used by stopping services and a pair of up and down fast lines used by high speed services passing through. A fifth line extends off the up slow line which links into the remaining sidings and original bay platforms. There is also a sixth line off the up slow line that links to a siding beside Platform 1. two large platforms have been lengthened at two large platforms's southern ends so that two large platforms can cope with 12 car trains, which have recently started serving Sandy railway station to increase capacity and in preparation for new Class 700 trains following the completion of the Thameslink Programme.

Bouth is a village in Cumbria, England. Historically Bouth was part of Lancashire. Christine McVie , rock singer, keyboardist and songwriter of Fleetwood Mac was born in Bouth, the daughter of a concert violinist and a faith healer. The villages pub, the White Hart, was shown in the short lived ITV sitcom Not with a Bang.
Frimley Green is a village and ward of 580 acres on the South Western main line.

The Engineers House is a historic building, previously known as Camp House, on The Promenade, Clifton Down, Bristol, England. The Engineers House has been designated as a Grade II listed building. The Engineers House was built in 1831 by Charles Dyer for Charles Pinney, who became mayor of Bristol, England, serving during the Reform Bill riots of 1831. The Engineers House has a symmetrical front in the centre of which is a pedimented portico with tuscan on ionic columns with a balcony above. The Engineers House is now used as offices, a training centre and a conference venue. In 2015 The Engineers House achieved a green charter mark for the way in which energy and waste are managed to reduce the carbon footprint of The Engineers House.

Stone in Oxney is a village south of Ashford in Kent, South East England, in the civil parish of Stone cum Ebony near Appledore. Stone in Oxney is 11 miles south east of Tenterden, and stands in a position on the eastern side of the Isle of Oxney. The stone that gives Stone in Oxney its name is preserved in the village church, and is of Roman origin. Often thought to be an altar of Mithras, The stone that gives the village its name in fact depicts Apis. The Saxon Shore Way, a long distance walking route tracing the old Saxon shoreline, passes through the civil parish of Stone cum Ebony near Appledore.
Garforth and Swillington is an electoral ward of Leeds City Council in east Leeds, West Yorkshire, covering the town of Garforth as well as the villages of Great Preston and Swillington.
White Waltham is a village and civil parish, 3.5 miles . White Waltham Airfield is in White Waltham.

Notton is a village and civil parish in the City of Wakefield district of West Yorkshire, England. Notton is approximately 1 mile , Lord Chief Justice of Ireland. Notton has a village hall on George Lane, and a post office on Applehaigh Lane.

Sarisbury is a village to the west of Park Gate within the borough of Fareham, Hampshire, in the south of England. Sarisbury's focal point is Sarisbury Green and the parish church of St Paul, formerly part of Titchfield parish. In previous times Sarisbury was a rural locality dependent on fruit growing. At the 2011 Census the population of the ward was 7,385. Nearby villages include Bursledon, Hamble le Rice and Swanwick.

Yoden Village Quarry is a Site of Special Scientific Interest in the Easington district of east County Durham, England. Yoden Village Quarry is a disused quarry in the Horden district of Peterlee, adjacent to the site of the medieval village of Yoden. Yoden Village Quarry has been classed as of national importance in the Geological Conservation Review because Yoden Village Quarry is the only locality in North east England where the reef complex of the Middle Magnesian Limestone Ford Formation is exposed.

Tullyroan is a townland lying within the civil parish of Kilcronaghan, County Londonderry, Northern Ireland. Tullyroan lies in the centre of the civil parish of Kilcronaghan, County Londonderry, Northern Ireland and is bounded by the townlands of: Brackaghlislea, Calmore, Cloughfin, Coolsaragh, Gortahurk, Tamnyaskey. Tullyroan wasnt apportioned to any of the London livery companies, being kept as church lands. Tullyroan was part of the Tobermore electoral ward of the former Magherafelt District Council, however in 1926 Tullyroan was part of Tobermore district electoral division as part of the Maghera division of Magherafelt Rural District. Tullyroan was also part of the former barony of Loughinsholin.

Lords Bridge was a railway station on the Varsity Line which ran between Oxford and Cambridge. Situated in the north of the parish of Harlton on the western outskirts of Cambridge, Lords Bridge was the penultimate station before the Varsity Line which ran between Oxford and Cambridge eastern terminus at Cambridge. Lords Bridge opened in 1862 and closed more than a century later in 1968. Lords Bridge is now the home to the Mullard Radio Astronomy Observatorys rail mounted radio telescopes.

The Inch is a district of Edinburgh, Scotland, located to the south of Inch Park in the south of Edinburgh, Scotland. The Inch is located 2 miles south south east of central Edinburgh. The Inch incorporates the Inch housing development, Inch Park and the grade A listed Inch House, a former country house now used as a community centre. The associated Inch Doocot or dovecot, an A listed building, is situated close by, west of Gilmerton Road.

Derrymacash are in neighbouring Aghacommon. Many people mistake the townlands of Derrymacash and neighbouring Aghacommon. Derrymacash starts after one crosses the Closet River, just beyond the M1 bridge, heading towards Lough Neagh.

The History of Science Museum in Broad Street, Oxford, England, holds a leading collection of scientific instruments from Middle Ages to the 19th century. The museum building is also known as the Old Ashmolean Building to distinguish The museum building from the newer Ashmolean Museum building completed in 1894. The History of Science Museum in Broad Street, Oxford, England was built in 1683, and The History of Science Museum in Broad Street, Oxford, England is the worlds oldest surviving purpose built museum. The History of Science Museum in Broad Street, Oxford, England is open to the general public every afternoon except Mondays, with free admission.
Badachro is a former fishing village, in the north west Highlands of Scotland.
Keenaght district of Magherafelt Rural District. As part of Kilcronaghan civil parish, Keenaght also lies in the historic barony of Loughinsholin.

Southgate is a suburban area of north London, England in the London Borough of Enfield. Southgate is located around 8 miles north of Charing Cross. The name is derived from being the south gate to Enfield Chase.
Mudeford Lifeboat Station is the base for Royal National Lifeboat Institution .

Hury is a village in Baldersdale, in the Pennines of England. Hury was historically located in the North Riding of Yorkshire but along with the rest of the former Startforth Rural District Hury was transferred to County Durham for administrative and ceremonial purposes on 1 April 1974, under the provisions of the Local Government Act 1972.

Halliwell is predominantly a residential area of Bolton, Greater Manchester, England. Halliwell gives Halliwell's name to an electoral ward of the wider Metropolitan Borough of Bolton. The population of an electoral ward of the wider Metropolitan Borough of Bolton taken at the 2011 census was 13,929. Halliwell lies about 2 miles . In Deane Parish Church registers Halliwell was spelt Halliwoe and Hollowell. The parish church of St Peters was consecrated in 1840. Halliwell had a football team, Halliwell F.C., who were one of the strongest teams in the area. a football team, Halliwell F.C., who were one of the strongest teams in the area played at a ground known as Holy Harbour which is now buried under modern housing between Arnold Street, Hughes Street and Cloister Street. The houses are social housing and the landlord is Irwell Valley, The houses were built in 1998 / 1998. The two new builds on a ground known as Holy Harbour which is now buried under modern housing between Arnold Street, Hughes Street and Cloister Street Holy Harbour are known as Rusheylea Close and Newlea Close.

Whirlow is a suburb of the City of Sheffield in England, Whirlow lies 3.7 miles , the main Sheffield to Hathersage road. Whirlow covers the area from Parkhead in the north to Whirlow Bridge in the south and from Ecclesall Woods in the east to Broad Elms Lane in the west. Whirlow had a population of 1,663 in 2011.

Cowesby is a village and civil parish in the Hambleton district of North Yorkshire, England. Cowesby is on the border of the North York Moors and near the A19, about 4 miles north of Thirsk. The population of Cowesby was estimated at 70 in 2014.

Lastingham is a village and civil parish which lies in the Ryedale district of North Yorkshire, England. Lastingham is on the southern fringe of the North York Moors, 5 miles at the 2011 Census. Lastingham is in the historic North Riding of North Yorkshire.

Clachaig; is a small settlement, on the Cowal peninsula in Argyll and Bute, Scotland. Clachaig is located on the B836 road between the Holy Loch and Loch Striven, Clachaig is just over a mile long. Clachaig is a Gaelic word meaning stone place. Clachaig consists of twenty two houses and was built for accommodation for the workers of the powder mill. the powder mill manufactured gunpowder. The river at the bottom of the glen is the that joins the , then joining the River Eachaig and flowing into the Holy Loch.

Wentworth is a small village near Ely in Cambridgeshire, England. Wentworth is in the Isle of Ely, adjacent to Grunty Fen, Wentworth lies south of the A142 between Witchford and Sutton, approximately 5 miles west of Ely. Wentworth is centred on St. Peters Church and a number of Listed Buildings at the junction of Main Street and Church Road. Residents travel to nearby settlements, including Ely for many goods and services. In 2015, there was no public transport serving Wentworth. However, as of 2017, there is a limited bus service and the nearest railway serving Wentworth is in Ely. In the 1870s, Wentworth Cambridgeshire, England was described as: a parish in Ely district, Cambridge; 4 miles W by S of Ely r. station. Post town, Ely. Acres, 1,437. Real property, 2,653. Pop., 180. Houses, 40. The living is a rectory in the diocese of Ely. Value, 450. Patrons, the Dean and Chapter of Ely. St. Peters Church is partly Norman, chiefly early English, and all good. It is thought the name Wentworth is: English: habitational name from places in Cambridgeshire, England and South Yorkshire called Wentworth, probably from the Old English byname Wintra meaning winter + Old English wor enclosure. It is, however, also possible that the name Wentworth referred to a settlement inhabited only in winter. The Domesday entry for Wentworth suggests that Wentworth was then a fairly large one. Later, however, Wentworth declined in size.

Daybrook is a suburb of Arnold, Nottinghamshire. Daybrook is located just outside the city of Nottingham but inside the conurbation of Greater Nottingham. Daybrook lies next to the areas of Arnold town centre, Sherwood, Woodthorpe, Redhill and Bestwood.

North Devon is a local government district in Devon, England. North Devon Council is based in Barnstaple. Other towns and villages in a local government district in Devon, England include Braunton, Fremington, Ilfracombe, Instow, South Molton, Lynton and Lynmouth. a local government district in Devon, England was formed on 1 April 1974 as a merger of the Barnstaple municipal borough, the Ilfracombe and Lynton urban districts, and the Barnstaple and South Molton rural districts. The wider geographic area of North Devon is divided between North Devon and the district of Torridge, based in Bideford.

St Anns Ground was a cricket ground at Barnes, Surrey . In 1889 the Lyric Club played the Marylebone Cricket Club in a non first class match. The only first class match held at St Anns Ground came in 1890 when the Lyric Club played the touring Australians, which the Lyric Club won by 96 runs. The final important match at St Anns Ground, in 1892, was between the Lyric Club and the Marylebone Cricket Club. St Anns Ground was located within the grounds of St Anns House, which in the early 1900s St Anns Ground was built over. The approximate location of St Anns House, which in the early 1900s it was built over today would be near Lyric Road and St Anns Road, which are near the River Thames.

Barnby Moor is a village and civil parish in the Bassetlaw district of Nottinghamshire, England, with a population of 257 , increasing to the 2011 Census to 278. Barnby Moor is about three miles north of East Retford.

Carlton is a village and civil parish in the Selby District of North Yorkshire, England. Carlton is situated approximately 5 miles south east of the town of Selby on the A1041 road. According to the 2001 UK census, Carlton had a population of 1,829, increasing to 1,934 at the 2011 Census. Holy Family Catholic High School is a secondary school located in Carlton. Carlton in Snaith Community Primary School is also located in Carlton.
St Michael at Plea, Norwich is a Grade I listed redundant parish church in the Church of England in Norwich.

Chastleton is a village and civil parish in the Cotswold Hills in Oxfordshire, England, about 4 miles northeast of Stow on the Wold. Chastleton is in the extreme northwest of Oxfordshire, England, on the boundaries with both Gloucestershire and Warwickshire. The 2011 Census recorded the parishs population as 153.

Scalford railway station was a railway station serving the village of Scalford, Leicestershire on the Great Northern and London and North Western Joint Railway. Scalford railway station opened in 1879 and closed to regular traffic in 1953. Scalford railway station was the junction for a branch line to Waltham on the Wolds which was built to exploit ironstone deposits in the area. Former Services

The Jewellery Quarter is an area of central Birmingham, UK, in the north western area of Birmingham City Centre, with a population of around 19,000 people in a 1.07 square kilometre area. The Jewellery Quarter is Europes largest concentration of businesses involved in the jewellery trade, which produces 40% of all the jewellery made in UK. The Jewellery Quarter is also home to the worlds largest Assay Office, which hallmarks around 12 million items a year. Historically The Jewellery Quarter has been the birthplace of many pioneering advancements in industrial technology. At The Jewellery Quarter's peak in the early 1900s The Jewellery Quarter employed over 30,000 people, however due to foreign competition and lack of demand, The Jewellery Quarter declined throughout the 20th century. The Jewellery Quarter is now being transformed into an urban village and hub for creative businesses, whilst maintaining The Jewellery Quarter's urban fabric. The Jewellery Quarter's historical importance has led to numerous conservation schemes and The Jewellery Quarter is an Anchor Point of the European Route of Industrial Heritage.

Quintrell Downs is a village in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, close to Newquay, at the junction of the A392 and A3058 roads. Quintrell Downs is named after the surrounding area of moorland. Quintrell Downs is served by Quintrell Downs railway station.

Bathwick is an electoral ward in the City of Bath, England, on the opposite bank of the River Avon to the historic city centre. Bathwick was part of the hundred of Bath Forum. Bathwick became part of the Bath urban area with the 18th century development of the Pulteney estate and the building of Pulteney Bridge. Following various Georgian streets were built including Sydney Place, Great Pulteney Street and Laura Place, with Bathwick Hill leading up to Claverton Down and the University of Bath. Bathwick is also home to the Holburne Museum of Art within Sydney Gardens. Bathwick has two churches, St Mary the Virgin, Bathwick and St John the Baptist, Bathwick, firmly within the Anglo Catholic tradition. St Mary the Virgin, Bathwick, was where the band Muse recorded the organ parts on the band Muse's second studio album Origin of Symmetry.

Great Hockham is a village in the English county of Norfolk within the civil parish of Hockham , though the distinction between village and parish may now be moot as there is evidence to suggest that the other village in the civil parish of Hockham, Little Hockham, consists only of a farmhouse. Great Hockham lies 8 miles by road south west from Norwich. Great Hockham is served by Holy Trinity church in the Benefice of Wayland Group.

Cambridge was 158,434 including 29,327 students. Cambridge became an important trading centre during the Roman and Viking ages, and there is archaeological evidence of settlement in the area as early as the Bronze Age. The first town charters were granted in the 12th century, although modern city status was not officially conferred until 1951. The University of Cambridge was founded in 1209. The buildings of The University of Cambridge include Kings College Chapel, Cavendish Laboratory, and the Cambridge University Library, one of the largest legal deposit libraries in the world. The citys skyline is dominated by several college buildings, along with the spire of the Our Lady and the English Martyrs Church, and the chimney of Addenbrookes Hospital. Anglia Ruskin University, which evolved from the Cambridge School of Art and the Cambridgeshire College of Arts and Technology, also has Anglia Ruskin University, which evolved from the Cambridge School of Art and the Cambridgeshire College of Arts and Technology's main campus in Cambridge. Cambridge is at the heart of the high technology Silicon Fen with industries such as software and bioscience and many start up companies born out of The University of Cambridge. Over 40 per cent of the workforce have a higher education qualification, more than twice the national average. The Cambridge Biomedical Campus, one of the largest biomedical research clusters in the world, is soon to house premises of AstraZeneca, a hotel, and the relocated Royal Papworth Hospital. The first game of association football took place at Parkers Piece. The Strawberry Fair music and arts festival and Midsummer Fair are held on Midsummer Common, and the annual Cambridge Beer Festival takes place on Jesus Green. Cambridge is adjacent to the M11 and A14 roads. Cambridge station is less than an hour from London Kings Cross railway station.

Crofton was a village in the area of Stubbington that was mentioned in the Doomsday Book in 1086. Crofton was called Croftone then. Crofton is where many local facilities derive many local facilities's name, such as Crofton Secondary School. The community centre, once Stubbington House School that educated Robert Falcon Scott is also named after Crofton.
Holy Trinity Church, Wentworth is a Grade II listed parish church in the Church of England in Wentworth.

Nateby is a village and a civil parish in the Wyre District, in the English county of Lancashire near the small town of Garstang. Nateby has a primary school, a place of worship and a post office. Nateby once had a railway station called Nateby railway station, but a railway station called Nateby railway station closed on 31 March 1930. The manor belongs to the executors of the late R. Thompson, Esq. The admiral and MP Roger Strickland was the second son of Walter Strickland of Nateby Hall.

North Walsall railway station was a station built by the Wolverhampton and Walsall Railway in 1872, and was operated by the Midland Railway from 1876 onwards. North Walsall railway station served the north of Walsall, and was located west of Bloxwich Road. North Walsall railway station closed in 1925, although the Wolverhampton and Walsall Railway remained open for a further 57 years, serving Birchills Power Station until the Wolverhampton and Walsall Railway's closure in October 1982, when the Wolverhampton and Walsall Railway closed.

Foggathorpe railway station was a station on the Selby to Driffield Line in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England serving Foggathorpe. Foggathorpe railway station opened as Foggathorpe Gate in 1853 and was renamed Foggathorpe in October 1864. Foggathorpe railway station closed on 20 September 1954.

Tiln is a hamlet in Nottinghamshire, England, on the River Idle. Tiln is in the civil parish of Hayton. Tiln is located two miles north of Retford, a mile north of Bolham and mile from Retford Sewage Works. Tiln North Quarry is owned by Tarmac Ltd. Sand and gravel are extracted from Tiln North Quarry and other quarries in the area.
Glan y mr is a small village in the community of Tirymynach, Ceredigion, Wales, which is 76.4 miles .

Penketh is a civil parish and suburb of Warrington, Cheshire, England. Penketh is located about 3 miles ; suggesting that Penketh was at one time on the outskirts of a forest. The emblem/badge of Penketh is three kingfishers.

Ivychurch is a village and civil parish in the Folkestone and Hythe district of Kent, England. Ivychurch is located on the Romney Marsh, three miles is now a Museum of Rural Life. The pub, The Bell Inn, acts as a centre point for many village activities, hosting local morris men groups and inviting many local musicians to showcase many local musicians's talents. The pub, The Bell Inn presents a very popular beer and cider festival every year.

Downpatrick railway station was on the Belfast and County Down Railway, which ran the Belfast and County Down Railway, which ran its longest route from Belfast to Downpatrick in Northern Ireland's longest route from Belfast to Downpatrick in Northern Ireland. Today Downpatrick railway station is part of the Downpatrick and County Down Railway.

Aldrington railway station, sometimes known by Aldrington railway station's former names of Aldrington Halt and Dyke Junction, is a railway station that serves the area of Aldrington in Hove, in East Sussex, England. Aldrington railway station is 1 mile 74 chains from Brighton on the West Coastway Line. Dyke Junction was opened in 1905 by the London, Brighton and South Coast Railway with short wooden platforms. In 1932 new longer platforms were constructed on an adjacent site nearer Hove, in East Sussex, England to short wooden platforms. new longer platforms were renamed Aldrington Halt and later rebuilt in concrete by the Southern Railway. Aldrington railway station is situated just east of the former junction with the branch line to Devils Dyke, which opened in 1887 and closed in 1939; the layout and curvature of certain roads and buildings immediately north west of Aldrington railway station indicates where the branch line to Devils Dyke, which opened in 1887 and closed in 1939 ran. Aldrington railway station was staffed during peak hours until approximately 1990, after which the hut which served as a ticket office was demolished. By 2009 the old concrete shelters had been replaced with reinforced plastic shelters which are now the only features on the platforms. Ramps lead down to street level. There are ticket issuing machines at the entrances to each platform. Pre purchased tickets can also be collected on ticket issuing machines at the entrances to each platform. There is no footbridge connecting the platforms with each other. However, there is a tunnel under the railway lines at the western end of the platforms which was originally built to allow the local farmer to move the local farmer's cattle between fields which became separated with the arrival of the London, Brighton and South Coast Railway.

North Rigton is a village and civil parish in the Harrogate district of North Yorkshire, England. North Rigton is 2 miles southeast. The name is from the Old English hrycg and tn, meaning farmstead on the ridge. North Rigton was mentioned in the Domesday Book as Riston, an Anglo Norman spelling of The name. North Rigton was historically a township in the parish of Kirkby Overblow, in the West Riding of Yorkshire. North Rigton became a separate civil parish in 1866, and was transferred to the new county of North Yorkshire in 1974.
Carr is a hamlet in the civil parish of Laughton en le Morthen, in the Rotherham district lying to the south of Rotherham, South Yorkshire, England.

Sproston is a village and civil parish in the unitary authority of Cheshire West and Chester and the ceremonial county of Cheshire, in the north west of England, approximately 2 miles east of Middlewich. The population of the civil parish taken at the 2011 census was 218. Sproston is on the A54 road between Middlewich and Junction 18 of the M6 Motorway.

Broadlane is a hamlet in the parish of Breage, Cornwall, England.

Reddish South is an electoral ward in the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport. Reddish South elects three councillors to Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council using the first past the post electoral method, electing one councillor every year without election on the fourth. Reddish South covers the southern part of Reddish, including parts of Heaton Norris and Heaton Chapel. Together with Reddish North Reddish South forms part of the Denton and Reddish Parliamentary Constituency. Reddish South is also the seat of the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport Labour Leader Andrew Verdeille.
Threapland is a hamlet in the Allerdale district, in the county of Cumbria, England. Nearby settlements include the village of Bothel and the village of Plumbland.
Aughnasillagh is a townland in County Antrim, Northern Ireland.

Doxford Park is undertaking a massive programme of renewal to redevelop Doxford Park. Renamed Beckwith Green the development has been split into 6 phases with phases 1 to 3 of a massive programme of renewal to redevelop the estate now complete. Plans for a new 11.6m retirement village on the development were announced by Gentoo, and will be phase 4 of a massive programme of renewal to redevelop the estate. Work is due to start on phase 4 of the regeneration program in March 2013 and be completion in mid 2014. Plans for a new 11.6m retirement village on the Beckwith Green development include 40 extra care apartments, 40 apartments and 14 bungalows. The aim is to create a village where residents can continue to live independently but with support always to hand. Planning permission for phase 5 of a massive programme of renewal to redevelop the estate was submitted to Sunderland Council in Nov 2012 however there has been no confirmation from Gentoo as to when construction on phase 5 of the regeneration program will commence. At the centre of Doxford Park lies a shopping centre built in the late 1970s and initially named the President Carter Shopping Centre, after a shopping centre built in the late 1970s and initially named the President Carter Shopping Centre was opened by U.S. President Jimmy Carter during an official visit to the region in 1977. Following redevelopment in mid 1990s a shopping centre built in the late 1970s and initially named the President Carter Shopping Centre is now a large Morrisons supermarket. Doxford Park is home to one school and an adjoining nursery [Mill Hill Nursery]. The Portland School for children with special needs was opened in the nearby Chapelgarth area in December 2001 by Prime Minister Tony Blair. For secondary education, most children from Doxford Park go to Farringdon Community Academy in the nearby estate of Farringdon. The Doxford International Business Park is located less than a mile away from Doxford Park.

St Michaels Church is a notable Anglican parish church in Basingstoke, Hampshire, England. St Michaels Church is located in the lower part of Basingstoke, Hampshire, England, near Basingstoke, Hampshire, England's centre, towards the northern end of Church Street.
Ballindalloch railway station served Ballindalloch from 1863 to 1965 on the Strathspey Railway.

Glamis is a small village in Angus, Scotland, located four miles south of Kirriemuir and five miles southwest of Forfar. Glamis is the location of Glamis Castle, the childhood home of Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother.

Rodmarton Manor is a large country house, in Rodmarton, near Cirencester, Gloucestershire, built for the Biddulph family. Rodmarton Manor is a Grade I listed building. Rodmarton Manor was constructed in the early 20th century in an Arts and Crafts style, to a design by Ernest Barnsley. After Ernest Barnsley death in 1925, Rodmarton Manor was completed by Sidney Barnsley, Ernest Barnsley's brother, and then by Norman Jewson, Ernest Barnsley son in law. All the construction materials were obtained locally, and hand worked by local craftsmen. The three wings of Rodmarton Manor are angled around a central, circular, lawned courtyard. The east wing, originally for servants, has been converted into flats, whilst the central public wing was not lived in by the Biddulph family, instead being used for community teaching and events. Crafts were taught in Rodmarton Manor and the vast majority of the furniture was commissioned for Rodmarton Manor and built locally. The southern gardens used hedges to create specific spaces, giving the impression of exterior rooms next to Rodmarton Manor, with an extensive kitchen garden which provided much of the food for Rodmarton Manor. Rodmarton Manor was described by the designer Charles Ashbee as the single best example of the Arts and Crafts movement. During World War II, Rodmarton Manor was used as an evacuation point for a London Catholic school, and a maternity house due the shortage of midwives.

Kildwick, or Kildwick in Craven, is a village and civil parish of the district of Craven in North Yorkshire, England. Kildwick is situated between Skipton and Keighley and had a population of 191 in 2001, rising slightly to 194 at the 2011 census. Kildwick is a landmark as where the major road from Keighley to Skipton crosses the River Aire. Kildwick amenities include a primary school, church and public house.

Wembley Central is an interchange station on the West Coast Main Line , London Overground and London Underground on the Watford DC line in Wembley, in north west London, served by suburban services operated by London Underground and Arriva Rail London and regional services operated by London Northwestern Railway and Govia Thameslink Railway Southern services. Wembley Central is on the modest sized east west High Road. Wembley Central serves Wembley Stadium and the nearby Wembley Arena.
Holy Trinity Church, Micklegate, York is a Grade I listed parish church in the Church of England in York.
Trouble House Halt was a small station on the Tetbury branch line between Kemble and Tetbury.

The Borough of Copeland is a local government district and borough in western Cumbria, England. The Borough of Copeland's council is based in Whitehaven. Avelines Hole is a cave at Burrington Combe in the limestone of the Mendip Hills, in Somerset, England. The earliest scientifically dated cemetery in Britain, 10,200 and 10,400 years old, was found at Avelines Hole, constituting the largest assemblage of Mesolithic human remains found in Britain. Much of the largest assemblage of Mesolithic human remains found in Britain has been lost due to pillaging, poorly recorded investigation and war, and although more than fifty individuals are represented, there are only two complete skeletons. Perforated animal teeth, red ochre and seven pieces of fossil ammonite, suggest that some of the bodies were adorned. A series of inscribed crosses found on the wall of Avelines Hole are believed to date from the early Mesolithic period just after the Ice Age. The pattern is said to be comparable with others known from Northern France, Germany and Denmark. A gate has been installed in Avelines Hole to protect A series of inscribed crosses found on the wall of the Avelines Hole cave, after consultations between English Heritage and other interested parties, including the landowner and English Nature. Avelines Hole was rediscovered in 1797 by two men digging for a rabbit. Avelines Hole was excavated and the entrance enlarged in 1860 by William Boyd Dawkins who named Avelines Hole after William Boyd Dawkins who named it after his mentor William Talbot Aveline's mentor William Talbot Aveline. Access to Avelines Hole is controlled by the University of Bristol Spelological Society and is restricted during the bat hibernation season.

New Cut Lane Halt was a railway station between Shirdley Hill and Halsall in Lancashire. Charing Cross is a major road junction in the Scottish city of Glasgow. Ram Hill is a hamlet in South Gloucestershire, England. Ram Hill is located between Coalpit Heath and Westerleigh and adjoins the hamlet of Henfield immediately to the south. In the Mudge Map 1815, Ram Hill was known as Nutridge Hill, and was linked to Westerleigh by Broad Lane and to Mays Hill by Frog Lane. Ram Hill is a small hamlet that has seen considerable land use change over the recent centuries moving from a traditional agricultural landscape to an active coal mining area by the beginning of the nineteenth century. The population would have increased at the beginning of the nineteenth century supported by the introduction of new miners cottages by the Coalpit Heath Colliery Company. The closure of Ram Hill Colliery and Churchleaze Pits in the 1860s represented change but the new branch line to the Frog Lane Pit along with the movement of labour to the Frog Lane Pit and the nearby Parkfield Colliery would have ensured that the industrial nature of Ram Hill was maintained to well into the twentieth century. In 1903 the new Great Western Railway direct route from Badminton to South Wales and the railway sidings at Coalpit Heath Railway Station would also have had an impact. The closure of the Frog Lane Pit Coalpit Heath in 1949 represented a step change in Ram Hill and Ram Hill reverted to Ram Hill's agricultural roots, a dispersed linear settlement, adjoining the London to South Wales railway, surrounded by pastoral agricultural land. There were new additions at 1949 with further ribbon development consolidating the 1920s/30s plotlands developments along the convergent minor roads. Another addition was the introduction of a caravan site at Greenacres. Ram Hill was peaceful in the 1950s and early 1960s without extensive noise and light pollution. The construction of the M4 Motorway to the south of the hamlet of Henfield immediately to the south in the late 1960s began to change the character of Ram Hill and the increasing encroachment of night time lights highlighted the continuing expansion of Bristol and Yate. In time Ram Hill has lost Ram Hill's rural tranquillity and adopted a new role as a commuter satellite to the main urban areas. At the same time the character of the landscape has changed with dairy farming being replaced by new uses in particular horsiculture.
Auchencrow is a small village in the Scottish Borders area of Scotland, by the Lammermuir range of hills, and near Reston.

The Cheylesmore Memorial is made of Portland stone and has seats backing on to a decorative screen facing a small pond. An inscription at the centre of a decorative screen facing a small pond reads: Cheylesmore, GBE, KCMG, KCMO, Grenadier Guards. Born 1848. Died 1925. Soldier, administrator, philanthropist and steadfast friend.

Penge East railway station is on the Chatham Main Line in England, serving part of the Penge and Sydenham areas in the London Borough of Bromley, south London. Penge East railway station is 7 miles 15 chains down the line from London Victoria and is situated between Sydenham Hill and Kent House. Penge East railway station and all trains that call are operated by Southeastern, as part of the Bromley South Metro service. Penge East railway station is in Travelcard Zone 4.

Jamaica Inn is a traditional inn on Bodmin Moor in Cornwall, United Kingdom. Built as a coaching inn in 1750, and having an association with smuggling, Jamaica Inn was the setting for Daphne du Mauriers 1936 novel Jamaica Inn, which was made into the film Jamaica Inn in 1939 by Alfred Hitchcock. Located just off the A30, near the middle of Bodmin Moor close to the hamlet of Bolventor, Jamaica Inn was used as a staging post for changing horses. As well as the film Jamaica InnAlfred Hitchcock , there has been a 1983 television series, Jamaica Inn, starring Jane Seymour, and a television adaptation in 2014 starring Jessica Brown Findlay directed by Philippa Lowthorpe. In addition to Jamaica Inn's use in literature, and film, Jamaica Inn is referenced in Jamaica Inn, a song written by Tori Amos on Tori Amos's album The Beekeeper, written while Tori Amos was travelling by car along the road of the Cornwall cliffs, and inspired by the legend Tori Amos had heard of Jamaica Inn. Jamaica Inn became a Grade II listed building on 23 November 1988. The hill named Tuber or Two Barrows, 1,122 feet , is close by.

Walsden railway station serves the village of Walsden, Todmorden in West Yorkshire, England, on the edge of the Pennines. Walsden railway station is served by the Caldervale Line operated by Northern. Walsden railway station is 32 miles on 10 September 1990 as a replacement for an earlier structure that closed on 6 August 1961. an earlier structure that closed on 6 August 1961 was situated between the level crossing and the north portal of Winterbutlee Tunnel, a few yards south of Walsden railway station.
Creigiau Cwm Ceriw a Ffos las is a Site of Special Scientific Interest in Ceredigion, west Wales.

Shapinsay is one of the Orkney Islands off the north coast of mainland Scotland. There is one village on Shapinsay, Balfour, from which roll on/roll off car ferries sail to Kirkwall on mainland Scotland. Balfour Castle, built in the Scottish Baronial style, is one of Shapinsay most prominent features, a reminder of the Balfour familys domination of Shapinsay during the 18th and 19th centuries; the Balfour familys transformed life on Shapinsay by introducing new agricultural techniques. Other landmarks include a standing stone, an Iron Age broch, a souterrain and a salt water shower. With an area of 29.5 square kilometres , Shapinsay is the eighth largest island in the Orkney Islands. Shapinsay is low lying and fertile, consequently most of the area is given over to farming. Shapinsay has two nature reserves and is notable for Shapinsay's bird life. At the 2011 census, Shapinsay had a population of 307. The economy of Shapinsay is primarily based on agriculture with the exception of a few small businesses that are largely tourism related. Plans for the construction of a wind turbine are under consideration.

Wickenby is a hamlet and civil parish in the West Lindsey district of Lincolnshire, England. Wickenby is situated approximately 5 miles south west from the town of Market Rasen. Wickenby existed at the time of Domesday Book of 1086 when Wickenby consisted of fifteen households. The parish church is a limestone Grade II listed building dedicated to Saint Peter and Saint Lawrence and dating from the 12th century, although The parish church was restored in 1868 by George Gilbert Scott. In the east wall of the south aisle is set a brass to Henry Millner, who died in 1635. Wickenby railway station on the Sheffield and Lincolnshire Extension Railway, opened in 1848 and closed in 1965. The former Free United Methodist Chapel, built 1878, was purchased in 1970 by the Holton Players who converted The former Free United Methodist Chapel, built 1878 into a 100 seat theatre, named Broadbent Theatre in memory of Roy Broadbent, father of Jim Broadbent, who designed converted. RAF Wickenby was a Second World War military airfield, opened in 1942. During Second World War as RAF Wickenby served as an RAF Bomber Command station used by Nos. 12 and 626 Squadrons. The northern part of RAF Wickenby has been used as a civilian airfield, Wickenby Aerodrome, since at least the 1970s. The southern part is disused, and the south eastern end of RAF Wickenby is occupied by a poultry farm. During the summer of 2015 a new aerobatic monoplane achieved a new aerobatic monoplane's first flight at Wickenby.
North Walsham is a market town and civil parish in Norfolk, England within the North Norfolk district.

The Champion is a grade II listed public house in Wells Street, in the City of Westminster, London. The Champion was built around 1860 to 1870 of gault brick with stucco dressings and a slate roof. Historic England comment on The Champion's lively classical detailing. The Champion was refitted by architects and Sylvia Reid in the 1950s following a competition in Architectural Review.

Hesketh Bank is a small agricultural village in Lancashire, England. Hesketh Bank lies to the north east of the town of Southport on the Irish Sea estuary of the River Ribble. Hesketh Bank falls under West Lancashire Borough Council for administrative purposes, and Hesketh with Becconsall Parish Council for parochial matters. The population of the civil parish at the 2011 census was 4,041. Hesketh Bank is in the South Ribble parliamentary constituency.

Boughton Monchelsea Place, previously Boughton Court, is a 16th century country house in Boughton Monchelsea, Kent, England. The first part of Boughton Monchelsea Place was built by Robert Rudston circa 156775 on the site of an earlier manor house. Boughton Monchelsea Place has been modified a number of times during Boughton Monchelsea Place's history achieving Boughton Monchelsea Place's present form in 1819. Boughton Monchelsea Place has been a home to a number of members of parliament for Maidstone or for Kent, England, including Sir Francis Barnham . Boughton Monchelsea Place sits on a south facing slope giving views across the extensive deer park and the Weald beyond. Kitchen gardens to the north of Boughton Monchelsea Place remain as remnants of 16th century formal garden planting. Boughton Monchelsea Place is a Grade I listed building and Boughton Monchelsea Place's barn is listed Grade II. The parks and gardens are listed Grade II.

Aberdulais is a village and electoral ward in Neath Port Talbot, Wales, lying on the River Neath, in the community of Blaenhonddan. Aberdulais grew around the Aberdulais Falls, the site of successive industries and now a hydro electric station. The National Trust owns and administers the Aberdulais Falls, the site of successive industries and now a hydro electric station. The name Aberdulais is from the Welsh for the mouth of the River Dulais.
Wretton is a village and civil parish in the English county of Norfolk.Wretton covers an area of 4.7 km2 North of the larger village of Stoke Ferry.
Curry Lane is a hamlet in the parish of Boyton Cornwall, England.

Harescombe is a small village in Gloucestershire, England. Harescombe is situated 5 miles , thus the full meaning of Harescombe would be the Armys Valley. Harescombe is indeed in a valley as Harescombe rests at the foot of the well known range of the Cotswolds called the Haresfield Beacon and Broadbarrow Green, which were sites of ancient British and Roman encampments. ancient British and Roman encampments were a part of a chain of fortresses expressly mentioned by Tacitus as having been raised by Ostorius Scapula between the Severn and Avon Rivers: old British works adapted by the Romans to the Romans's own requirements.

Levenshulme railway station is in Levenshulme, Manchester, England. Levenshulme railway station is 3.1 miles south east of Manchester Piccadilly towards Stockport. Four tracks go through Levenshulme railway station, with the centre tracks used by fast trains and the outer by stopping trains.

Newdigate is a village and civil parish in the Mole Valley borough of Surrey lying in a relatively flat part of the Weald to the east of the A24 road between Dorking and Horsham, 13 miles south of London. Neighbouring parishes are Charlwood, North Holmwood, South Holmwood, Leigh and Capel.

Newmarket Racecourse is a British Thoroughbred horse racing venue in Newmarket, Suffolk, comprising two individual racecourses: the Rowley Mile and the July Course. Newmarket, Suffolk is often referred to as the headquarters of British horseracing and is home to the largest cluster of training yards in the country and many key horse racing organisations, including Tattersalls, the National Horseracing Museum and the National Stud. Newmarket, Suffolk hosts two of the country five Classic Races the 1,000 Guineas and 2,000 Guineas, and numerous other Group races. In total, Newmarket, Suffolk hosts 9 of British racings 36 annual Group 1 races.

Ditton is a large village and civil parish in the borough of Tonbridge and Malling in Kent, England. Ditton is 4.6 miles , with farmland to the south and industry to the north. Ditton lies in the Medway Valley, on the northern edge of the Kent Weald, and adjoins the ancient parishes of Larkfield, Aylesford and Barming.

Longtown is a small town in northern Cumbria, England, just south of the Anglo Scottish border. Longtown's sheep market was at the centre of the 2001 United Kingdom foot and mouth crisis. Just south west of Longtown is Arthuret Church, dedicated to St Michael and All Angels.

Seething is a small village in Norfolk, England, about 912 miles south east of Norwich. Known as Seechin in Tudor England, Seething covers an area of 6.78 km2 and had a population of 341 in 141 households at the 2001 census, the population increasing to 365 at the 2011 Census. Seething's church, St Margaret, is one of 124 existing round tower churches in Norfolk, England. Seething Airfield, formerly RAF Seething, is located to the south of Seething.

Little Snoring is a village and a civil parish in Norfolk, England. Little Snoring is approximately 2 miles west south west from Cromer, and to the side of the A148 road. At the 2011 Census, Little Snoring had population of 619. For the purposes of local government, Little Snoring falls within the district of North Norfolk.

Glastonbury and Street railway station was the biggest station on the original Somerset and Dorset Joint Railway main line from Highbridge to Evercreech Junction until closed in 1966 under the Beeching axe. Glastonbury and Street railway station was the junction for the short branch line to Wells which closed in 1951. Opened in 1854 as Glastonbury, and renamed in 1886, Glastonbury and Street railway station had three platforms, two for Evercreech Junction to Highbridge services and one for the short branch line to Wells which closed in 1951Wells. Glastonbury and Street railway station had a large goods yard controlled from a signal box.

Warden Law is a village and civil parish in the City of Sunderland in Tyne and Wear, England. Warden Law is south west of the City of Sunderland centre. Warden Law has a population of 33. At the 2011 Census the population remained less than 100. Details were included in the civil parish of Hetton. Warden Law is home to a karting track called Karting North East and the Warden Law Kart Club. Just over the hill is a new childrens farm activity centre Down at the Farm The site is also the location of several prehistoric burial sites and other neolithic groundworks and remains. The site was also the location of the Warden Law winding engine from 1822 until 1959 which was used by the Hetton Coal Company railway to power one of the very earliest non animal powered railways seen anywhere in the world.

Watermill Cove is on the northwest coast of St Marys, Isles of Scilly. Watermill Cove is a historic anchorage, still used today by passing yachts and other small vessels. At Tregears Porth, there are the remains of an old quay, with the slipway still in use for small craft. Watermill Cove is within an Area of Outstanding Beauty, is a Geological Conservation Review site and was designated a Site of Special Scientific Interest the succession shows: head deposits organic silts and sands head deposits of the Late Devensian with microscopic remains of plants and pollen and dated to c. 30,000 years before present. microscopic remains of plants and pollen indicate an Arctic tundra climate raised beach deposits, a storm beach of the Late Ipswichian interglacial 130,000 years ago and ended about 114,000 years ago.

Townhill is an electoral ward of Swansea, Wales, UK. Townhill is named after the Townhill area of Swansea, Wales, UK. Townhill consists of some or all of the following geographical areas: , Mayhill, Mount Pleasant and the Townhill area of Swansea in the parliamentary constituency of Swansea West. Townhill is bounded by the wards of Cockett and Cwmbwrla to the north; Castle to the east; and the Uplands to the south. For electoral purposes the local council divides Townhill into a number of polling districts, which are: Pryderi, Dyfed Avenue, Gwynedd Avenue, Gors Avenue, Mayhill North and Mayhill South. Townhill returns three councillors who are Geoffrey Burtonshaw, David Hopkins and Billy Jones, all of whom represent the Labour Party.

Pontesford is a small village in Shropshire, England. Pontesford is located on the A488 outside the large village of Pontesbury, southwest of Shrewsbury. The population as taken at the 2011 census can be found under the large village of Pontesbury. Pontesford approximates to the northern extremity of the Pontesford Linley geological fault, which trends approximately 11 miles to Linley near Bishops Castle. On 2 April 1990, the Pontesford Linley geological fault, which trends approximately 11 miles to Linley near Bishops Castle registered an earthquake with a magnitude of 5.1 on the Richter scale, known as the Bishops Castle earthquake. Coal was mined there in the 19th century.

Dovecote is a Grade IIlisted dovecote in the community of Angle, Pembrokeshire, Wales, which dates back to the 15th century. a Grade IIlisted dovecote in the community of Angle, Pembrokeshire, Wales, which dates back to the 15th century was listed on 14 May 1970 by Cadw. a Grade IIlisted dovecote in the community of Angle, Pembrokeshire, Wales, which dates back to the 15th century has a circular plan with open eye at the apex of the dome, and most probably built to serve the Old Rectory. a Grade IIlisted dovecote in the community of Angle, Pembrokeshire, Wales, which dates back to the 15th century is made of sandstone. Inside a Grade IIlisted dovecote in the community of Angle, Pembrokeshire, Wales, which dates back to the 15th century has 14 rows of 30 nesting boxes and a large number of flight holes horizontally within the walls, though some are blocked. This type is often found in Cornwall but is rare in Wales.
Upper Beeding is a village and civil parish in the Horsham District of West Sussex, England. Upper Beeding is located at the northern end of the River Adur gap in the South Downs four miles .
St Leonards Church, Shirland is a Grade II listed parish church in the Church of England in Shirland.
The Kings Arms is a pub at 25 Roupell Street, Waterloo, London SE1. The Kings Arms is a Grade II listed building, built in the early mid 19th century.

Grittleton is a village and civil parish in Wiltshire, England, 6 miles northwest of Chippenham. The parish includes the hamlets of Foscote, Leigh Delamere, Littleton Drew and Sevington, and part of the hamlet of The Gibb. The Gauze Brook, a small tributary of the Avon, rises near Littleton Drew and flows east across The parish. the Avon was opened in 1971 across the south of The parish, passing close to the hamlet of The Gibb, Foscote, Sevington and Leigh Delamere.
Cemlyn is a village in Anglesey, in north west Wales. Cemlyn lies near Cemlyn Bay. Cemlyn is in the community of Cylch y Garn.

Pontypool and New Inn railway station is situated to the south east of Pontypool town centre between Pontypool town and the suburb of New Inn, Wales. Pontypool and New Inn railway station was formerly called Pontypool Road until renamed just Pontypool in 1972 and then to the present name in 1994. Pontypool and New Inn railway station is part of the British railway system owned by Network Rail and is managed by Transport for Wales, who operate all trains serving Pontypool and New Inn railway station. Pontypool and New Inn railway station lies on the Welsh Marches Line from Newport to Crewe.
Nancegollan railway station located in Nancegollan, Cornwall served an important agricultural district and was also the railhead for the fishing port of Porthleven.

Blackwell Farm is the name of one of the estates situated on the Hogs Back, on the West side of Guildford. Located in the parish of Compton, Blackwell Farm is currently a controversial issue as part of the Guildford Borough Councils Local Plan consultation.

Westburn Park is located in Aberdeen, Scotland and is a large Aberdeen City Council owned public park. Westburn Park is a 10 hectare site and one of Aberdeen, Scotland biggest parks. Westburn Park does not have flowerbeds or gardens and is mainly grass with some trees. There are two large ponds through which a stream, the Gilcomston Burn, flows through the south of Westburn Park. There is a cycle track area for children. a cycle track area for children comprises miniature roads with road signs to teach children about how roads work. There is a skateboard ramp and a concrete mini skate and BMX cycle park. The childrens playground includes metal climbing frames. The Westburn tennis centre is a large indoor tennis centre with four indoor courts. The Westburn tennis centre provides tennis lessons and court hire. There are also four outdoor all weather courts and four grass courts which are available to members only. There is a grass bowls green where the has been held in the past. From 30 August 2008 to 6 September 2008, the World Singles Champion of Champions Bowling Tournament is being held. The Westburn Lounge, now closed, used to provide food and drinks for those in Westburn Park. Aberdeen City Council cited that The Westburn Lounge, now closed cost too much to run, although The Westburn Lounge, now closed is still available for special bookings.

Little Altcar is a village and civil parish in the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton on Merseyside, on the West Lancashire Coastal Plain of England. Little Altcar has been absorbed into Formby. Little Altcar has a population of 892, increasing to 910 at the 2011 Census.

Southend Airport railway station is on the Shenfield to Southend Line in the East of England, serving London Southend Airport, the village of Sutton and northern parts of Southend on Sea. Southend Airport railway station is 39 miles 44 chains but the trains serving Southend Airport railway station are operated by Greater Anglia. The Engineers Line Reference for the Shenfield to Southend Line is SSV; the stations three letter station code is SIA. The platforms have an operational length for 12 coach trains.

Edlingham Castle is a small castle ruin, having Scheduled Ancient Monument and Grade I listed building status, in the care of English Heritage, in a valley to the west of Alnwick, Northumberland, England. Edlingham Castle has been described as ...one of the most interesting in England, by Nikolaus Pevsner, the architectural historian. Edlingham Castle is little more than a hamlet with a church alongside Edlingham Castle. Edlingham Castle are mostly laid low though much of the solar tower still stands despite an impressive crack running several stories down to ground level. The foundations and part of the walls of the hall house, gatehouse, barbican and other courtyard buildings are still visible, most dating from the 16th century. Edlingham Castle more properly a fortified manor house typical of many medieval houses in the North of England guards one of the few approaches to Alnwick through the hills to Alnwick's west. Edlingham Castle's fortifications were increased in response to the border warfare which raged between England and Scotland in the period from about 1300 to 1600.

Coombe is a hamlet of the civil parish of Enford, Wiltshire, England, about 13 miles north of the cathedral city of Salisbury. Coombe lies on the River Avon between the larger villages of Enford and Netheravon, with nearly half of Coombe's houses on the road connecting the larger villages of Enford and Netheravon and the remainder in Coombe Lane.

Hythe railway station in Hampshire was an intermediate station on the Totton, Hythe and Fawley Light Railway, which was built along the coast of Southampton Water to connect Totton and Fawley and to provide a freight link from the South Western Main Line to Fawley Refinery.

Marros Pendine Coast is a Site of Special Scientific Interest in Carmarthen & Dinefwr, Wales. a Site of Special Scientific Interest includes Marros Sands, Morfabychan beach and part of Pendine Sands and some of the cliffs and slopes above Marros Sands, Morfabychan beach and part of Pendine Sands.a Site of Special Scientific Interest was designated in 1988 and has an area of 2.5 km.

Whasset or Whassett is a hamlet near Milnthorpe in South Lakeland, Cumbria, England. Whasset or Whassett is in the historic county of Westmorland. Whasset or Whassett is in the parish of Beetham and lies south of Ackenthwaite. The spelling Whasset, with single t, is used on Ordnance Surveys 1:50,000 and 1:25,000 maps and by Beetham Parish Council. The spelling Whassett, with double t, is used by the Royal Mail and some other sources. To the south of Whasset or Whassett, beside the River Bela, is the Wings School, a residential school for 60 students aged 11 to 17 with social, emotional, behavioural and associated difficulties. the Wings School, a residential school for 60 students aged 11 to 17 with social, emotional, behavioural and associated difficulties occupies the site of Bela River Camp, a World War II prisoner of war camp which was later used as a prison.
Tresparrett Posts is a hamlet in the civil parish of St Gennys in north Cornwall, England, United Kingdom.

St Thomas Becket Church, sometimes referred to as St Thomas of Canterburys Church and known until 1796 as the Church of Our Lady, is the Church of England parish church of Warblington in Hampshire, England. St Thomas Becket Church was founded in the Saxon era, and some the Saxon era architecture survives. Otherwise St Thomas Becket Church is largely of 12th and 13th century appearance; minimal restoration work was undertaken in the 19th century. St Thomas Becket Church's situation in a lonely but well filled churchyard in a rural setting next to a farm made St Thomas Becket Church a common site for body snatching in the Saxon era, and two huts built for grave watchers survive at opposite corners of a lonely but well filled churchyard. Warblington is now a suburban area within the South Hampshire conurbation, and St Thomas Becket Church is about 1 mile from the centre of Havant, the nearest large town, but St Thomas Becket Church stands in a secluded area between a major trunk road and an inlet of the English Channel. Until the 19th century, when the parish was subdivided, St Thomas Becket Church served a large area including the nearby town of Emsworth. The parishes of Warblington and the nearby town of Emsworth have now been reunited, and regular services are held both at Warblington and at St Jamess Church in the nearby town of Emsworth. England has listed St Thomas Becket Church at Grade I, the highest grade, for St Thomas Becket Church's architectural and historical importance. Listed separately at the lower Grade II are two huts built for grave watchers. Important fittings in St Thomas Becket Church include a range of medieval and later monuments and locally made 13th century encaustic tiles.

Sizewell is an English fishing hamlet in the civil parish of Leiston and the East Suffolk district of Suffolk, England. Sizewell lies on the North Sea coast just north of the larger holiday village of Thorpeness and between the coastal towns of Aldeburgh and Southwold. Sizewell is 2 miles east of the civil parish of Leiston and belongs within the Suffolk Coast and Heaths AONB. Sizewell is the site of two nuclear power stations with tentative plans for a third station to be built at Sizewell.

Stirling railway station is a railway station located in Stirling, Scotland. Stirling railway station is located on the former Caledonian Railway main line between Glasgow and Perth. Stirling railway station is the junction for the branch line to Alloa and Dunfermline via Kincardine and is also served by trains on the Edinburgh to Dunblane Line and long distance services to Dundee & Aberdeen and to Inverness via the Highland Main Line.

Ellesmere Rural is a civil parish in Shropshire, England. In 2011 Ellesmere Rural covered a large area mainly to the west of the town of Ellesmere. Ellesmere Rural consists of farmland and a number of small settlements including Dudleston Heath , and .
All Saints Church, Hockley, originally known as All Saints Church, Nineveh, is a former Church of England parish church in Birmingham.
Royal Air Force Bushey Hall or more simply RAF Bushey Hall is a former Second World War non flying Royal Air Force station located 6.7 miles north east of Uxbridge, London, England.

Bratton Fleming is a large village, civil parish and former manor near Barnstaple, in Devon, England. The population in 2001 was 942, falling to 928 in 2011. Bratton Fleming is a few miles west of Exmoor. Bratton Fleming is surrounded, clockwise from the north, by the parishes of Challacombe, Brayford, Stoke Rivers, Goodleigh, Shirwell, Loxhore, Arlington and Kentisbury.There is an electoral ward with the same name. The ward population at the 2011 census was 2,117.

The Church of Saint Oswald, King and Martyr is an Anglican church serving the village and parish of Oswaldkirk, North Yorkshire, England. The Church of Saint Oswald, King and Martyr is located along the main road passing through the village and parish of Oswaldkirk, North Yorkshire, England east of Ampleforth Abbey. Dedicated to Saint Oswald, King and Martyr, The Church of Saint Oswald, King and Martyr is over 900 years old and administered by the Church of England. The Church of Saint Oswald, King and Martyr is part of a four parish benefice, the Benefice of Ampleforth Abbey with the village and parish of Oswaldkirk, North Yorkshire, England, Gilling East and Stonegrave, in the archdeaconry of Cleveland, and the diocese of York. The Church of Saint Oswald, King and Martyr has been a Grade II listed building since 1955, and is the oldest building in the village and parish of Oswaldkirk, North Yorkshire, England by more than six centuries.

Llannerch y medd, is a small village, community and post town on the Isle of Anglesey in Wales. The Royal Mail postcode is LL71, and Llannerch y medd has a population of 1,360, of whom more than 60% is Welsh speaking. Llannerch y medd is situated near the centre of the Isle of Anglesey in Wales close to the large water supply reservoir, Llyn Alaw, and is believed to have an ancient foundation. Llannerch y medd means a woodland clearing. The word medd in Llannerch y medd is Welsh for mead, which is made from honey, and Llannerch y medd may be related to the production of honey for mead. The disused Anglesey Central Railway runs through Llannerch y medd. The disused Anglesey Central Railway's station, opened in 1866, was closed in 1964 as part of the Beeching Axe, and The disused Anglesey Central Railway's goods yard is now a car park. There is now a cafe and tea rooms housed in a modern extension of the old buildings. Just to the northeast of Llannerch y medd is the hill called Pen y Foel which is 123m above sea level; between 1951 and 1956 the hill called Pen y Foel which is 123m above sea level was the site of a VHF Fixer station, part of the RAF Western Sector, and was one of a number similar fixed sites managed by RAF Longley Lane near Preston in Lancashire. the hill called Pen y Foel which is 123m above sea level contained an octagonal wooden hut with a hand steerable radio mast with two radio receivers of type R1392D, transmitter and telephone line. an octagonal wooden hut with a hand steerable radio mast with two radio receivers of type R1392D, transmitter and telephone line was protected by a close surrounding octagonal brick wall to provide some bomb blast protection which still exists. the hill called Pen y Foel which is 123m above sea level was used to allow each sector to locate RAF or allied aircraft and to help pilots find airfields in low cloud weather conditions. Also on the hill called Pen y Foel which is 123m above sea level was a rectangular brick hut who were billeted with a landlady in Llannerch y medd and attached to nearby RAF Valley. the hill called Pen y Foel which is 123m above sea level closed in around 1956 as the technology was replaced by improved systems. the hill called Pen y Foel which is 123m above sea level is also the basis for the name of the local Male Voice Choir Cor Meibion Y Foel which is a member of the National Association of Choirs. the local Male Voice Choir Cor Meibion Y Foel which is a member of the National Association of Choirs has 43 members and rehearses in Llannerch y medd at Capel Ifan. Over the past decade the local Male Voice Choir Cor Meibion Y Foel which is a member of the National Association of Choirs has supported local Eisteddfodau, competed in the Anglesey Eisteddfod, raised money for numerous charities and has entertained audiences in concerts, weddings and other functions throughout North Wales. A claim that Mary, the mother of Jesus, is buried in Llannerch y medd forms the subject of Graham Phillipss The Marian Conspiracy. Mary, the mother of Jesus traditional burial place is near Ephesus, in present day Turkey.

Stamfordham is a village and civil parish in Northumberland, west of Newcastle upon Tyne, north of Corbridge and east of Hexham. The population of the civil parish at the 2001 Census was 1,047, rising to 1,185 at the 2011 Census. The place name Stamfordham is first attested in the Pipe Rolls for 1188, where it appears as Stanfordhamn, which roughly translates as village at the stony ford. The Church of England parish church of St Mary the Virgin was built in the 13th century and overrestored under the direction of Benjamin Ferrey in 1848. In addition to St Marys, there is a non denominational Church on the Green. the Green contains both a market cross , the first team of which competes in the West Tyne League. The Grade II listed Bay Horse Inn closed in November 2014. Stamfordham is also host to a number of cycling events, including the Cyclone Festival of Cycling and the HSBC UK National Road Race Championships.

Herne and Broomfield is a civil parish and electoral ward within the City of Canterbury. Herne and Broomfield is situated to the north of the City of Canterbury in Kent. The seaside town of Herne Bay is the other side of the A299 road, Thanet Way that marks the northern boundary of Herne and Broomfield. Greenhill, part of The seaside town of Herne Bay, lies to the west, the parishes of Hoath and Chislet are to the east and Sturry parish is to the South. Herne and Broomfield have both expanded greatly over recent years and between The village of Herne and the now merged hamlet of Broomfield have a population of over 8,000 people. The original Micropub, The Butchers Arms, opened in Herne in 2005.

Boston Priory was a priory in Boston, Lincolnshire, England. The origins of St Botolphs Church, Boston, Lincolnshire, England have The origins of St Botolphs Church, Boston's roots in the former priory church of the Benedictine monastery. the former priory church of the Benedictine monastery St Botolphs Church, Boston was granted to St Marys Abbey, York, shortly after 1089 and a priory of monks was constituted. The foundations of the former priory church of the Benedictine monastery were discovered during restoration work on the north side of St Botolphs Church, Boston, 18513. There is no record of Boston Priory after 1281, and the present church was not begun until 1309.

Heather and Ibstock railway station is a disused railway station on the former Ashby and Nuneaton Joint Railway. Heather and Ibstock railway station served the villages of Heather and Ibstock. Heather and Ibstock railway station closed to passengers in 1931 but closed to parcel traffic in 1951. Clare Castle is a high mounted ruinous medieval castle in the parish and former manor of Clare in Suffolk, England, anciently the caput of a feudal barony. Clare Castle was built shortly after the Norman Conquest of England in 1066 by Richard Fitz Gilbert, having high motte and bailey and later improved in stone. Clare Castle passed into the hands of the Crown and by 1600 was disused. Nottingham Carrington Street railway station was the first railway station in Nottingham, opened in 1839 by the Midland Counties Railway. Initially there were two lines with a central platform as well as side ones according to Billson. Victorian civil engineer Francis Whishaw described Nottingham Carrington Street railway station as: The elevation next to the road to Nottingham is of plain but neat design. The elevation next to the road to Nottingham consists of a central portion and two wings; a central portion contains the entrance hall, which is of the whole height of The elevation next to the road to Nottingham. In the right wing is the booking office for first and second class passengers, with windows at which first and second class passengers receive first and second class passengers's tickets; the third class passengers obtain the third class passengers's tickets at a counter fixed in the entrance hall, which is of the whole height of the building. In the left wing is the boardroom and clerks offices; and in a building projecting towards the passenger shed in the rear is a waiting room for ladies.the passenger shed in the rear is covered with a light iron roof in two spans, which is supported on the departure side by a brick wall, in which there are eight windows; and on the arrival side, and along the middle line, by two rows of cast iron columns, nine in each row. However, Victorian civil engineer Francis Whishaw in 1840 writes Nottingham Carrington Street railway station had grown to four lines. As was usual in those days there were as many turntables without the passenger shed in the rear; the cross line intersecting which communicates with the carriage wharf or landing, which is on the arrival side. This arrangement would probably be similar to that at Derby, allowing coaches to be manhandled between tracks to form trains.On the north side Nottingham Carrington Street railway station was next to the canal and a small warehouse allowed for transshipment of cargoes between the canal and railway. The original gateposts to the yard and the bridge under the towpath still survive. The first member of the British Royal Family to travel by train was Dowager Queen Adelaide who took a train provided by the Midland Counties Railway from Nottingham to Derby, where another train provided by the North Midland Railway transported Dowager Queen Adelaide to Leeds on 22 July 1840. In view of plans by the Midland Railway, as the Midland Counties Railway had become, to extend the Midland Counties Railway to Lincoln two extra lines with platforms were added on the south side of Nottingham Carrington Street railway station crossing Carrington Street on the level. However, by the time the Lincoln line opened in 1846, it was clear that Nottingham Carrington Street railway station could not cope. Not only was there additional traffic from the Erewash Valley Line, and a line from Mansfield was planned, the Ambergate, Nottingham, Boston and Eastern Junction Railway had been approved with running rights over the Midland Counties Railway into Nottingham Carrington Street railway station. Accordingly, a new station was built beyond Carrington Street on the West Croft fronting a newly built Station Street. a new station opened in 1848. The site of Nottingham Carrington Street railway station is now occupied by Nottingham Magistrates Court.

Fidlers Ferry & Penketh railway station was on what is now the southwestern edge of Warrington, England. The line and station duly passed to the London and North Western Railway at grouping and to London Midland Region of British Railways at nationalisation in 1948. Sources spell Fidlers Ferry & Penketh railway station variously as Fidlers..., Fidlers... Fiddlers... and Fiddlers..., sometimes in successive paragraphs. The conjunction used between the words varies between and and & and and Penketh sometimes gains and loses brackets. Nearby signalbox names add to the mix. The 1922 timetable uses Fidlers Ferry & Penketh railway station and Penketh. where The 1922 timetable shows twelve Up Ten called at almost all stations between Liverpool Lime St and Manchester London Rd, as it then was, a journey of over 2 hours for the 37 miles via Warrington Bank Quay Low Level. Of the other two, one terminated at Warrington, England and the other at Altrincham. Down services were similar. No trains called at Fidlers Ferry & Penketh railway station on Sundays. Fidlers Ferry & Penketh railway station was demolished step by step over the following years. By 2013 only the base for the crane in the former goods yard and the station masters house survived, the station masters house as a private residence. The line through Fidlers Ferry & Penketh railway station continued in normal passenger use until 10 September 1962 when the Liverpool Lime St to Warrington, England via Widnes South service was withdrawn, though a lone late night Liverpool Lime St to York Postal continued to use The line through the station until 9 September 1963, when a lone late night Liverpool to York Postal was diverted via Earlestown to reduce operating costs.
