Alum Rock is an electoral ward of Birmingham City Council in the east of Birmingham, West Midlands, covering an urban area to the east of the city centre. Alum Rock was created in 2018 as a result of boundary changes that saw the number of wards in Birmingham, West Midlands increase from 40 to 69.

Brighouse is a town within the metropolitan borough of Calderdale, in West Yorkshire, England. Historically within the West Riding of Yorkshire, Brighouse is situated on the River Calder, 4 miles the bridge over the River Calder. In Brighouse's early history, Brighouse was a hamlet of the nearby village of Rastrick. Brighouse is twinned with Ldenscheid in Germany, twinned beginning with an exchange by Brighouse Childrens Theatre in 1950 followed by a civic twinning charter in 1960.

Buchanstone railway station is a former railway station in Aberdeenshire. On the Great North of Scotland Railway, Buchanstone railway station was on the north side of the track. Buchanstone railway station was opened in November 1854 and closed to passenger traffic in September 1866. The building was demolished before 1901 and nothing visible remains. the Great North of Scotland Railway is still in use as the Aberdeen to Inverness Line.
St Chads Church, Derby was a Church of England parish church in Derby.

Pwllheli railway station is a railway station serving the small coastal town of Pwllheli on the Lln Peninsula in Gwynedd, Wales. Pwllheli railway station is the terminus of the Cambrian Coast Railway.

Wigton is a market town in Cumbria, England. Historically in Cumberland, Wigton lies just outside the Lake District in the borough of Allerdale. Wigton is at the centre of the Solway Plain, between the Caldbeck Fells and the Solway coast. Wigton is served by Wigton railway station on the Cumbrian Coast Line, and the A596 road to Workington. The town of Silloth on Solway lies 12 miles to the west, beyond Abbeytown.

New Castle Lachlan, is an 18th century baronial mansion or country house located at Strathlachlan, Cowal peninsula, Argyll and Bute, Scotland. an 18th century baronial mansion or country house was built in 1790 by Donald Maclachlan, 19th laird, to replace the 15th century Old Castle Lachlan, which stands nearby on the shores of Loch Fyne. an 18th century baronial mansion or country house is protected as a category C listed building. an 18th century baronial mansion or country house was remodelled around 1910 by the architect George Mackie Watson.

Stapleton Road railway station is on the Severn Beach Line and Cross Country Route, serving the inner city district of Easton in Bristol, England. Stapleton Road railway station is 1.6 miles from Bristol Temple Meads. Stapleton Road railway station's three letter station code is SRD. As of 2018, Stapleton Road railway station has two platforms, four running lines and minimal facilities. Stapleton Road railway station is managed by Great Western Railway, the seventh company to be responsible for Stapleton Road railway station, and the third franchise since privatisation in 1997. Great Western Railway, the seventh company to be responsible for the station, and the third franchise since privatisation in 1997 provide all train services at Stapleton Road railway station, the standard service being a train every 40 minutes along the Severn Beach Line, an hourly service to Bristol Parkway, and another hourly service to Westbury. Stapleton Road railway station was opened in 1863 by the Bristol and South Wales Union Railway, with a single track and platform. the Severn Beach Line was doubled in 1874 when the Clifton Extension Railway opened, then expanded to four tracks and platforms in 1888. There were buildings on all platforms and a goods yard to the north. Stapleton Road railway station became one of Bristol, England busiest stations, but service levels reduced significantly in the 1960s when reversing trains at Bristol Temple Meads became common. The goods facilities were closed in 1965, staff were withdrawn in 1967 and the Severn Beach Line was reduced to two tracks in 1984. In 2018, two additional running lines were added to increase capacity as part of the 21st century modernisation of the Great Western Main Line. the Severn Beach Line was also due to be electrified, but electrified has now been deferred until the next control period, which runs from 2019 to 2024.

Drayton is a residential area of the city of Portsmouth in the English county of Hampshire. Together with Farlington, Drayton's parent area, Drayton makes up one of the electoral wards of the city of Portsmouth.
The Longmead Stadium is an association football stadium in Tonbridge, Kent, England. The Longmead Stadium is home to Tonbridge Angels, who currently compete in the National League South.

Bishops Cleeve is a village in the Borough of Tewkesbury, Gloucestershire, north of Cheltenham. Bishops Cleeve lies at the foot of Cleeve Hill, the highest point in the Cotswolds, and borders Woodmancote on the east side of the Gloucestershire Warwickshire railway line that splits the two parishes. Bishops Cleeve had a population of 10,612 in 2011, and was estimated to be over 17,000 in 2018. Bishops Cleeve saw rapid growth during the 20th century as a result of the construction of Smiths Aerospace factory near Bishops Cleeve after the Second World War. Currently, population and residential growth is a contentious subject due to the vast expansion of the housing estates without increased amenities. At the moment, a bid for 500 more houses has been refused but is currently under appeal.

Higham Priory was a priory in Kent, England likely founded in 1148. Higham Priory was officially dissolved on 28 September 1524.

Marston Gate Railway station was a station on the London and North Western Railway Aylesbury Branch serving the nearby village of Long Marston, Hertfordshire.
